Cell.Text: The Greybeards? What do those old hermits want with me?

Node.Caption: MQ302TulliusIntroTopic: I have a message from the Greybeards.

Cell.Text: Why? There's nothing to discuss as long as that traitor Ulfric is in arms against his rightful Emperor.

Node.Caption: MQ302TulliusIntroA1: They're convening a peace council at High Hrothgar.

Node.ToolTip:
0004A209 - Custom, in use by kkuhlmann
Last User:kkuhlmann Date:4/25/2011 File:Skyrim.esm

Cell.Text: The best time to negotiate is from a position of strength.
Fair enough. We're driving the Stormcloaks back well enough at the moment, but we're already overstretched.
The war is stalemated. What's the harm in talking to Ulfric?
No, you're right. After all this time, Ulfric still holds almost half of Skyrim.
Better to negotiate than lose completely.
Well... we could use some breathing space to regroup. Things haven't been going well for us lately.

Node.Caption: MQ302TulliusIntroImperial: I think you know it's not as simple as that.

Cell.Text: Most of the Legion is tied down on the border with the Aldmeri Dominion. The Emperor can't afford to risk weakening Cyrodiil's defenses. | From the Imperial City, our war here is just a sideshow. An interlude before the main event against the Thalmor resumes.

Node.Caption: MQ302TulliusIntroB1A: Why won't the Emperor send more reinforcements?

Cell.Text: [S] G|Yes. Yes, fine, I'll come to this Greybeard council. For all the good it will do.

Node.Caption: MQ302TulliusIntroC1: You'll come to the peace council, then?

Cell.Text: It's about time they turned their gaze from the heavens, back to our bleeding homeland. What do they want?

Node.Caption: MQ302UlfricIntroTopic: I have a message from the Greybeards.

Node.ToolTip:
0001FC32 - Custom, in use by kkuhlmann
Last User:kkuhlmann Date:4/25/2011 File:Skyrim.esm

Cell.Text: I have the greatest respect for the Greybeards, of course. And the dragon attacks are a growing plague. | But the political situation is still delicate. Not all the jarls are fully committed to supporting me as High King. | I can't afford to appear weak. I can't agree to this unless Tullius himself will be there.

Node.Caption: MQ302UlfricIntroA1: They want to negotiate a truce until the dragon menace is dealt with.

Node.ToolTip:
0001FC31 - Custom, in use by kkuhlmann
Last User:kkuhlmann Date:4/25/2011 File:Skyrim.esm

Cell.Text: Good. Maybe he's realized he's beaten. The way things are going, we'll be knocking at the gates of Solitude itself before too long.
Good. We still hold half of Skyrim despite everything the Empire could throw at us. | I doubt the Empire has the stomach for much more bloodletting.
Good. They've had their victories, but Tullius is no fool. The Empire can't afford to keep this up much longer.

Node.Caption: MQ302UlfricIntroB1: General Tullius has already agreed to attend.

Node.ToolTip:
0001FC30 - Custom, in use by kkuhlmann
Last User:kkuhlmann Date:4/25/2011 File:Skyrim.esm

Cell.Text: I can't agree to any peace council until I know Tullius will be there. The other jarls could take that as a sign of weakness.

Node.Caption: MQ302UlfricIntroB2: General Tullius hasn't agreed to attend yet.

Cell.Text: He is weak. And no doubt knows it. He's no fool, he'll come, if only to give his troops a chance to refit. | But you're right. Victory is within our grasp. We can afford to give the Empire one more chance to withdraw.
You're right. Let Tullius be the one to insult the Greybeards by refusing their summons. | Show up these Imperials for the foreigners they really are.
Hmm. We could use the time to bring in new recruits. Our losses have been heavy recently...

Node.Caption: MQ302UlfricIntroC1: Tullius will look weak if he refuses, not you.

Node.ToolTip:
0001FC2E - Custom, in use by kkuhlmann
Last User:kkuhlmann Date:4/25/2011 File:Skyrim.esm

Cell.Text: [S] G|Yes. I'll give Tullius one more chance to quit Skyrim with his tail between his legs.

Node.Caption: MQ302UlfricIntroD1: So you'll come to the peace council?

Cell.Text: [S] You may have a point. It's getting difficult to even move troops around without attracting a dragon attack. | By all accounts the Stormcloaks are suffering just as badly. Even Ulfric might see the sense of a truce under these conditions.
I'll be the judge of that. Besides, by all reports the Stormcloaks are suffering just as much as we are from these dragon attacks.

Node.Caption: MQ302TulliusIntroB1New: The dragons are a bigger problem than the Stormcloaks right now. (Persuade)

Cell.Text: The best time to negotiate is from a position of strength.
True. A pause to consolidate our gains would be useful. And the Empire can afford to look magnanimous in victory.
Neither side is making much headway. What's the harm in talking to Ulfric?

Ulfric's insurrection has reached its high tide. Soon enough the rebel jarls will realize what it means to oppose the Empire. | But, as you say, these negotiations may offer a chance for his supporters to gracefully return to the Imperial fold.
I think you overestimate Ulfric's chances. He's stretched himself too thin. | But... we could use the breathing space to regroup.

Node.Caption: MQ302TulliusIntroStormcloak: You're not going to win this war on the battlefield.

Cell.Text: <<Shared>> That's what comes of trying to win a war with a bare handful of legions. If the Emperor would just give me the reinforcements I've requested!
They are getting to be a problem. But I wasn't sent to Skyrim to fight dragons. | My job is to quell this rebellion, and I intend to do just that, dragons or no dragons.

Node.Caption: MQ302TulliusIntroNewA1: We need a truce until the dragon menace is dealt with.

Cell.Text: Ulfric has already agreed to attend.

Has he? I suppose he doesn't want to miss a chance to bluster about the Empire's many crimes. | He's probably hoping I'll refuse so he can blame the Empire for being unreasonable. I think I'll have to disappoint him yet again.
Hmm. You may have a point. I'm always surprised by how seriously the Nords take these things.

Node.Caption: MQ302TulliusIntroB4: The Empire can't afford to snub the Greybeards.

Cell.Text: Alduin? The World-Eater of song and legend? If that's true... well, it changes the situation doesn't it? | Even Tullius may be forced to talk sense in the face of such a threat.

Alduin? The World-Eater of song and legend? If that's true, we're all doomed anyway. | And if it isn't true... well, then the fight to free Skyrim goes on. Either way, I don't see the use in talking to the Empire.

Node.Caption: MQ302UlfricIntroB3: Politics be damned. Alduin has returned! (Persuade)

Cell.Text: You speak truly, Dragonborn. Sometimes the grubby business of politics clouds my eyes. | Besides, it will be good to see High Hrothgar again.

Node.Caption: MQ302UlfricIntroC2: The Greybeards won't let the Empire take advantage of you.

Cell.Text: I don't need you to teach me how to play high politics in Skyrim. | But... you're right. There's nothing to be gained by refusing the Greybeards' request.

Node.Caption: MQ302UlfricIntroC3: Showing respect to the Greybeards will increase your prestige.
